-- ============================================================
-- SCULPTRA AESTHETIC
-- product_id: 2ce7a3d2-b06d-4b62-b9b7-4113afb51baa
-- Active ingredient: Poly-L-lactic acid (PLLA) microparticles
-- FDA-cleared: facial lipoatrophy in immunocompromised patients (2004); cosmetic correction of
--   shallow to deep nasolabial fold contour deficiencies and other facial wrinkles (2009)
-- Key mechanism: biostimulation — PLLA microparticles trigger collagen neogenesis (collagen I/III)
-- Onset: delayed (weeks to months); Peak: 3-6 months; Duration: 2+ years
-- Sessions: typically 2-3 treatment sessions spaced 4-8 weeks apart
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '1cc99870-cdda-49e0-af12-c7381584ad2a',
  '2ce7a3d2-b06d-4b62-b9b7-4113afb51baa',
  'a6a854e2-7db1-4ec0-bac0-7b346454fca0',
  'clinical', 'clinical_summary', 'provider',
  'Sculptra Aesthetic — Clinical Summary',
  E'## Product Identity\n\nSculptra Aesthetic is a sterile, injectable, biodegradable implant composed of **poly-L-lactic acid (PLLA) microparticles** (150 mg/vial) suspended in sterile water for injection with carboxymethylcellulose sodium and non-pyrogenic mannitol. Manufactured by Galderma. The PLLA microparticles are 40–63 µm in diameter — intentionally sized to be too large for phagocytosis, which sustains the inflammatory/fibroblastic response. [FDA label Sculptra Aesthetic NDA 021195]\n\nCritical distinction: **Sculptra is NOT a filler.** It does not add volume directly. The PLLA microparticles act as a scaffold that triggers fibroblast activation and endogenous collagen synthesis (primarily collagen Types I and III). Results are gradual, cumulative, and reflective of the patient''s own biological response. [FDA label; peer-reviewed: Vleggaar D. J Eur Acad Dermatol Venereol 2006]\n\n## Mechanism of Action\n\nAfter intradermal injection, PLLA microparticles initiate a controlled foreign-body inflammatory cascade:\n1. Macrophages surround the particles (cannot phagocytose at 40-63 µm)\n2. A fibrous capsule forms around each particle\n3. Fibroblasts are activated and deposit collagen within and around the capsule scaffold\n4. Over weeks to months, the PLLA hydrolyzes into CO₂ and H₂O; the scaffold is replaced by organized collagen matrix\n5. Net result: gradual volumetric correction through patient-derived collagen replacement\n\n[FDA label; peer-reviewed: Goldberg D. J Cosmet Laser Ther 2013; peer-reviewed: Vleggaar D. Dermatol Surg 2006]\n\nImplication for clinical management: onset is **delayed** (weeks to months), peak effect at approximately 3-6 months after a course of treatments. The patient leaves each session with no visible correction — volume builds between sessions and over the weeks following the final session. Managing patient expectations around this delayed mechanism is the central clinical communication challenge for this product. [field practice consensus]\n\n## FDA-Cleared Indications\n\n- **HIV-associated facial lipoatrophy:** Restoration of facial fat to restore normal facial proportions in immunocompromised patients (original 2004 approval). [FDA label]\n- **Cosmetic correction of shallow to deep nasolabial fold contour deficiencies and other facial wrinkles:** FDA approval for aesthetic indication in immunocompetent adults (2009). [FDA label]\n\n**Gateway posture — off-label uses:** Sculptra is used extensively off-label for diffuse facial volumization (temple hollowing, cheek volume, jawline), buttock augmentation ("Sculptra Butt Lift"), décolletage rejuvenation, and neck skin quality improvement. These are field-standard practices in experienced centers but are not FDA-labeled. Off-label use represents significant real-world volume for this product. [field practice; sources differ on technique and dosing for off-label anatomical sites — see relevant technique literature]\n\n## Candidacy\n\n**Ideal candidate profile:**\n- Adults with gradual, diffuse facial volume loss affecting multiple zones (rather than focal area needing point-correction)\n- Patients willing to commit to a multi-session protocol (2-3 sessions, 4-8 weeks apart) and understand the delayed onset\n- Those comfortable with a process-based correction where "patience is the protocol"\n- Patients seeking a natural, progressive result that doesn''t look sudden or done\n- Good candidates for combining with HA fillers later for surface refinement after Sculptra creates the collagen foundation [field practice; consensus]\n\n**Poor candidacy signals:**\n- Patients needing immediate volume correction (event in next 4-6 weeks)\n- Patients unable to commit to multi-session protocol\n- History of keloid formation (hypersensitive fibrotic response risk)\n- Active skin infection, inflammation, or autoimmune skin disease at injection sites\n- History of hypertrophic scarring at treatment sites\n- Unrealistic expectations regarding timeline or endpoint [FDA label]\n\n## Safety Profile\n\n**Adverse events [FDA label — authority rank 1]:**\n- Common: injection site bruising, swelling, tenderness, discomfort. Expected with any deep injection. Typically resolve within a few days to 2 weeks. [FDA label]\n- Nodules/papules: **subcutaneous papules** are the signature adverse event for PLLA and require proactive management. Two types:\n  - *Injection-site papules* (early, <2 weeks): from incorrect dilution, too-superficial injection, or too much product in one area — technique-dependent and preventable\n  - *Delayed nodules* (months post-injection): reported in early protocols; dramatically reduced with the current dilution protocol (≥5-8 mL diluent) and improved injection technique. [FDA label; peer-reviewed: Lowe NJ. Dermatol Surg 2005]\n- Late inflammatory nodule: rare; may require intralesional steroid or surgical removal [FDA label]\n\n**Critical safety practice:** The current FDA-recommended reconstitution protocol (at least 5-8 mL sterile water per vial) was established after early protocols using smaller diluent volumes led to higher papule rates. Strict adherence to reconstitution guidelines is mandatory. Many experienced injectors now use 8-10+ mL diluent to reduce particle concentration per depot. [FDA label; field practice consensus]\n\n**Contraindications:** Hypersensitivity to any component of Sculptra. Active infection or inflammation at injection sites. [FDA label]\n\n**No reversal agent exists** for PLLA — unlike HA fillers, papules cannot be dissolved enzymatically. Prevention through proper technique (correct dilution, correct depth, massage protocol) is the only management. This is a critical patient education point. [FDA label]\n\n## Clinical Outcomes Data\n\nOriginal FDA approval studies (HIV lipoatrophy): significant improvement in facial volume scores vs. placebo. [FDA label NDA 021195]\n\nCosmetic indication studies: significant improvement in NLF contour severity scores; most subjects required 3 sessions. Duration of effect: up to 25 months maintained in some study populations. [FDA label 2009 approval data]\n\n**Gateway posture:** Duration is quoted as "up to 2 years or more" in field practice with ranges varying widely by volume treated, number of sessions, patient age, and metabolism. For exact protocol and retreatment intervals, see the Sculptra Aesthetic Prescribing Information [FDA/DailyMed →].',
  '67666118-7ed4-4627-b873-031b7666ee94',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '51297ecf-e2ea-4714-b622-824724db1915',
  '2ce7a3d2-b06d-4b62-b9b7-4113afb51baa',
  'a6a854e2-7db1-4ec0-bac0-7b346454fca0',
  'clinical', 'technique_guide', 'provider',
  'Sculptra Aesthetic — Technique Guide',
  E'## Injection Planes\n\nSculptra must be injected into the **deep dermis or subcutaneous layer** — plane selection is critical because placement depth determines both efficacy and safety:\n\n- **Facial volumization:** Deep subcutaneous/subdermal plane — the product must be remote from the epidermis and superficial dermis to avoid visible papule formation. The goal is product within the deep fat compartments where collagen neogenesis provides volumetric correction.\n- **Nasolabial folds (FDA-labeled):** Deep dermis to subcutaneous at the fold. Mid-dermal injection in this area has higher papule risk. [FDA label technique description]\n- **Off-label sites (temples, malar, jawline, buttocks):** Supraperiosteal or deep subcutaneous depending on zone — more tissue depth is available in the malar and temporal areas. Buttock augmentation uses subcutaneous plane with very high dilution. [field practice — technique sources differ significantly]\n\n**Gateway posture:** Specific injection technique (cannula vs. needle, depot vs. threading, exact depth to periosteum) varies significantly between experienced practitioners. Sources differ on optimal approach per zone. For foundational technique, see the Sculptra Aesthetic prescribing information and approved technique education [FDA/DailyMed →].\n\n## Reconstitution Protocol (Safety-Critical)\n\nReconstitution is the most technically important step for PLLA and directly affects safety outcomes:\n\n- **Current FDA-recommended protocol:** Add ≥5 mL sterile water for injection per vial; many experienced practitioners use 8-10 mL to reduce particle concentration per depot. Allow vial to hydrate for at least 2 hours at room temperature (some protocols recommend overnight hydration at 4°C). [FDA label]\n- **Do not use immediately after reconstitution:** The hydration period allows PLLA particles to swell and distribute evenly in suspension; inadequate hydration time is associated with higher papule rates.\n- **Final product should be a smooth, milky-white homogeneous suspension** — no visible clumps. Gentle agitation, not vigorous shaking.\n- **Volume per session:** Ranges from 2-6 mL total per session depending on degree of correction needed, anatomical sites, and session number in protocol. [FDA label; field practice — sources differ on exact per-zone volumes]\n\n## Dosing Framework (Range Characterization)\n\nTotal volume delivered across a treatment course (not per session):\n- Moderate facial volume loss: typically 4-8 vials total across 2-3 sessions\n- Significant volume loss (HIV lipoatrophy or severe age-related): may require more\n- Buttock augmentation (off-label): significantly higher volumes — highly technique-dependent\n\n**Critical gateway pointer:** PLLA dosing is highly individualized; no fixed per-area prescription exists in the literature without extensive qualifications. Sources differ widely on vial counts and per-session volume. For dosing guidance, consult the Sculptra Aesthetic Prescribing Information, approved training materials, and peer-reviewed technique literature [FDA/DailyMed →].\n\n## Massage Protocol\n\nThe "5-5-5 rule" is widely cited in field practice for post-injection massage:\n- 5 minutes massage immediately after treatment\n- 5 times per day\n- 5 days after treatment\n\nThe rationale: massage distributes PLLA particles evenly and prevents clumping that leads to focal nodule formation. [field practice consensus; sources generally support this principle though exact protocol variants exist in the literature]\n\n## Treatment Planning\n\n- Sessions spaced 4-8 weeks apart to allow initial collagen response before additional stimulation\n- 2-3 sessions typical for moderate facial volume loss; 1-2 for maintenance/touch-up\n- Assess at 8-12 weeks after each session — not at the session itself\n- Progression photography at standardized angles is essential to document gradual change\n- Combination planning: Sculptra first (collagen foundation layer) → HA fillers later for point-correction of residual focal deficits → neurotoxin for dynamic component [field practice consensus]\n\n## Combination Sequencing\n\nSculptra is the "foundation layer" in combination planning when both PLLA and HA fillers will be used. The collagen matrix that Sculptra builds over months provides structural support that reduces the volume of HA filler required for surface refinement. Many experienced practitioners describe the sequence as: Sculptra for diffuse volume → assess at 6 months → targeted HA filler for remaining point-corrections. Sources differ on whether same-session combination is appropriate or should be staged. [field practice — sources differ]',
  '68ae5ce6-948a-45d6-b71d-672adaeebfb0',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'f17ef339-cb39-4512-8327-837125c0c1a1',
  '2ce7a3d2-b06d-4b62-b9b7-4113afb51baa',
  'a6a854e2-7db1-4ec0-bac0-7b346454fca0',
  'sales_education', 'patient_education', 'patient',
  'Sculptra Aesthetic — Patient Education',
  E'## What It Does for You\n\nSculptra Aesthetic works differently from any other aesthetic treatment you may have heard of — and that difference is exactly what makes it special.\n\nMost injectables add something to your face directly. Sculptra does something more elegant: it tells your skin to produce more of your own collagen. Sculptra''s active ingredient is poly-L-lactic acid (PLLA) — a biocompatible, biodegradable material used in medicine for decades (it''s the same material in many dissolvable sutures). When injected, the PLLA microparticles stimulate your fibroblasts — the cells responsible for making collagen — to produce new collagen over the weeks and months following treatment.\n\nThe result builds gradually and looks completely natural, because it IS natural. Your face doesn''t change overnight; it gets progressively better over months as your own collagen fills in and restores the structural architecture you''ve been losing since your mid-20s. By the time results are visible, most people simply look rested and refreshed — not "done."\n\n## The "Your Own Collagen" Narrative\n\nThis is the key distinction: Sculptra''s results are YOUR collagen. Not product. Not filler. Not a foreign substance staying in your face indefinitely. The PLLA particles gradually dissolve; what remains is your body''s own collagen matrix. This is why Sculptra results:\n- Look and feel completely natural (it''s your tissue)\n- Last 2+ years in most patients — collagen persists long after the PLLA is gone\n- Build progressively rather than appearing suddenly\n- Look better over time rather than immediately after treatment\n\n## The Multi-Session Protocol\n\nSculptra is not a one-and-done treatment — it''s a protocol. Most patients receive 2-3 sessions spaced 4-8 weeks apart. Here''s why this structure matters:\n\nEach session stimulates a new wave of collagen production. The sessions are spaced intentionally so the collagen response from each session has time to build before the next stimulation adds to it. Think of it like compound interest: each session adds to the base established by the previous one.\n\nAfter your final session, your skin continues to improve for another 2-3 months as the last collagen response peaks. **This is the treatment''s design, not a limitation.** Patience is literally part of the protocol.\n\n## What to Expect\n\n**During sessions:** After the area is cleansed, your injector will administer Sculptra through fine needle injections across the treatment zones. You will see immediate temporary swelling — this is the injection volume (sterile water) and will resolve over a day or two. You are NOT seeing collagen or volume yet; that comes later.\n\n**After sessions:** You will massage the treated areas 5 times per day for 5 days after each treatment. This is an important step in your protocol — it distributes the Sculptra evenly under your skin.\n\n**Between sessions and after:** Over the weeks and months following your treatment course, you will see gradual, progressive improvement. Most patients notice meaningful change at 3-4 months after their last session, with peak results at 6 months.\n\n**Duration:** Clinical data and real-world experience show results lasting 2 years or more in many patients. Because the results are your own collagen, they fade slowly and naturally — there''s no "wearing off" cliff.\n\n## Benefit Framing\n\nSculptra is for patients who want **restoration**, not correction. It addresses the underlying cause of facial aging — collagen and volume loss — rather than chasing individual wrinkles. The ideal Sculptra patient is someone who looks in the mirror and feels their face has lost its fullness, definition, or "lift," even though there''s no single line or fold they can point to.\n\n**The value story:** Spread across a 2+ year lifespan, Sculptra is one of the most cost-effective volumetric rejuvenation options available. The cost per month of visible result often compares favorably to HA fillers that require yearly retreatment. And unlike HA fillers, Sculptra''s result gets better before it gets less — you''re not watching filler disappear.\n\n## Combination Therapy\n\nSculptra is often the structural foundation of a comprehensive rejuvenation plan:\n- Sculptra first for diffuse volume restoration (the canvas)\n- After 6 months, HA filler for any remaining point-corrections (specific lines or focal areas)\n- Neurotoxin (Botox/Dysport) for dynamic expression lines throughout — Sculptra does not affect muscle movement\n- Energy-based treatments (RF microneedling, Morpheus8) can complement collagen stimulation — providers will advise appropriate timing and sequencing\n\nMany patients find that Sculptra reduces the amount of HA filler they need long-term, making the combination plan more economical over time.\n\n## Maintenance\n\nAfter your initial course achieves your baseline result, maintenance with a single session every 12-18 months keeps the collagen foundation supported. Because the result is gradual and stable, maintenance is about sustaining a result you''ve built — not correcting decline from scratch. Most patients settle into a rhythm of one treatment per year to stay ahead of ongoing collagen loss.',
  'ae3a04db-70ab-4302-a6fd-9e00bcb1b071',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '8aacef16-7560-4ef5-8a1d-a6c5cd357b09',
  '2ce7a3d2-b06d-4b62-b9b7-4113afb51baa',
  'a6a854e2-7db1-4ec0-bac0-7b346454fca0',
  'sales_education', 'faq', 'patient',
  'Sculptra Aesthetic — FAQ',
  E'## Common Questions\n\n**"Will I see results right away?"**\nNo — and that''s by design, not a limitation. Right after your session you''ll see temporary swelling from the injection liquid, which resolves in 1-2 days. The actual result — new collagen — builds progressively over the following weeks and months. Most patients see meaningful improvement at 3-4 months after completing their treatment course, with peak results around 6 months. This timeline is not a disadvantage; it''s what makes the result look so natural.\n\n**"How many sessions will I need?"**\nMost patients need 2-3 sessions, spaced 4-8 weeks apart. The exact number depends on the degree of volume correction needed and your individual collagen response. After your initial consultation, your provider will recommend a starting protocol — you''ll refine based on your response.\n\n**"How long does it last?"**\nClinical data supports 2 or more years of maintained improvement. Because the result is your own collagen (not a product that dissolves), the fade is very gradual and natural. Most patients schedule a maintenance session every 12-18 months to stay ahead of ongoing collagen loss.\n\n**"What''s the massage I''ve heard about?"**\nThe 5-5-5 rule: massage the treated areas 5 minutes, 5 times per day, for 5 days after each session. This step is important — it distributes the Sculptra evenly and prevents particle clustering that can cause small bumps. Your provider will walk you through this before you leave.\n\n**"Can it be reversed?"**\nSculptra works differently from HA fillers — there is no enzyme that dissolves it. The PLLA particles gradually break down on their own over time. This means prevention through proper technique is important. Choosing an experienced, trained injector significantly reduces risk. If a rare small bump forms, there are management options your provider can discuss.\n\n**"Is this the same as filler?"**\nNo. Dermal fillers (like Juvederm or Restylane) add volume directly by placing a gel under the skin. Sculptra does not add volume itself — it triggers your skin to make its own collagen. The result type is different: fillers provide immediate correction; Sculptra provides gradual, natural collagen restoration. Both are valuable; the right choice depends on your goal and timeline.\n\n## Objection Reframes\n\n**"I can''t wait months to see results."**\nThis objection is usually about an upcoming event or impatience with the process. For event-driven timelines, your provider can recommend HA fillers that deliver immediate results. For patients who want the best long-term outcome and can plan ahead, Sculptra''s delayed onset is the feature — gradual improvement looks completely undetectable, and the result outlasts any immediate correction.\n\n**"Multiple sessions sounds expensive."**\nThe multi-session cost compares favorably when spread over 2+ years of result. Many patients find that after a Sculptra course, they need less HA filler — the combination is often more economical over time than repeated filler-only maintenance. Your provider can help you understand the long-term value picture for your specific plan.\n\n**"I''m nervous about something that can''t be reversed."**\nThis is the right question to ask, and the right injector will appreciate it. The key answer: with experienced technique, correct dilution protocol, and proper injection depth, serious complications are rare. Sculptra has been in use since 2004 and has an established safety record. The reversibility concern is real — which is why the injector''s experience matters more for Sculptra than for HA fillers. Choose your provider carefully.',
  'ae3a04db-70ab-4302-a6fd-9e00bcb1b071',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'b5fd9933-11b3-46f7-bfc4-f767cf696b9a',
  '2ce7a3d2-b06d-4b62-b9b7-4113afb51baa',
  'a6a854e2-7db1-4ec0-bac0-7b346454fca0',
  'deep_product', 'deep_dive_playbook', 'provider',
  'Sculptra Aesthetic — Deep Dive Playbook',
  E'## Differentiation\n\nSculptra Aesthetic occupies a unique position in the injectable landscape because it is categorically distinct from all HA fillers, CaHA fillers, and neurotoxins. It is the only FDA-approved PLLA biostimulator for facial rejuvenation in the US market. Its core differentiation:\n\n1. **Mechanism:** Biostimulation (endogenous collagen induction) vs. direct volumetric fill\n2. **Timeline:** Gradual, progressive results vs. immediate correction\n3. **Result character:** Diffuse, natural volumization vs. localized focal correction\n4. **Longevity:** 2+ years vs. 9-24 months for most HA fillers\n5. **Reversibility:** Not reversible (no enzyme) vs. hyaluronidase-reversible for HA\n\nVersus Radiesse (CaHA): Both are non-HA biostimulators with longer duration than conventional HA. Key differences: Radiesse provides immediate direct volume AND biostimulation (dual mechanism); Sculptra is biostimulation-only (no immediate volume). Radiesse is FDA-indicated for NLF and hands; Sculptra for facial lipoatrophy and NLF. Duration comparison: Radiesse 12-18 months vs. Sculptra 2+ years. Technique requirements differ; Sculptra has stricter reconstitution protocol. [peer-reviewed: Palm M. J Drugs Dermatol 2010; field practice comparison]\n\nVersus HA Fillers: HA provides immediate volume via mechanical fill; reversible; typically 9-24 months. Sculptra is the complementary approach for diffuse volume — many practices combine them (Sculptra for foundation; HA for focal refinement).\n\n## Mechanism Detail\n\n**PLLA microparticle mechanism:**\n- Particle size (40-63 µm) is the key design parameter — too large for macrophage phagocytosis, ensuring sustained presence\n- Initial inflammatory response: macrophage recruitment, foreign-body giant cell formation\n- Fibroblast activation: direct fibroblast stimulation by PLLA surface chemistry and degradation fragments\n- Collagen production: primarily Type I and Type III collagen — the structural collagens responsible for skin firmness and volume\n- PLLA degradation: hydrolysis to lactic acid → CO₂ + H₂O over approximately 12-18 months\n- Net result: PLLA gone, collagen matrix remains\n\n[peer-reviewed: Goldberg D. J Cosmet Laser Ther 2013; peer-reviewed: Vleggaar D. Dermatol Surg 2006; FDA label NDA 021195]\n\n**Clinical implication of the mechanism:** The delayed onset means that a treatment session produces no visible immediate result for the provider to assess. Volume measurement is done at 8-12 week follow-up. Over-treatment risk is significant if providers attempt to "top off" too soon — the full response of early sessions has not yet manifested. The reconstitution and dilution protocol is designed to control dose per depot to avoid particle overconcentration. [field practice consensus]\n\n## Evidence Summary\n\n**HIV lipoatrophy FDA approval (2004):** Pivotal data: significant improvement in facial volume (skin thickness, fat restoration) vs. placebo in HIV-positive patients. [FDA label NDA 021195]\n\n**Aesthetic indication FDA approval (2009):** Multi-center, controlled study. Primary endpoint: improvement in NLF severity score at 13 months. Sustained efficacy demonstrated to 25 months. [FDA label 2009 supplement]\n\n**Key publications:**\n- Vleggaar D. J Eur Acad Dermatol Venereol 2006 — PLLA collagen stimulation mechanism\n- Vleggaar D. Dermatol Surg 2006 — European long-term data\n- Goldberg D. J Cosmet Laser Ther 2013 — Collagen stimulation histological evidence\n- Lowe NJ. Dermatol Surg 2005 — Papule prevention; reconstitution protocol development\n- Palm M. J Drugs Dermatol 2010 — Comparative biostimulator overview\n\n## Comparison Anchors\n\n| Parameter | Sculptra Aesthetic | Radiesse | Juvederm Voluma XC |\n|-----------|-------------------|----------|--------------------|\n| Active ingredient | PLLA microparticles | CaHA microspheres | HA (Vycross) |\n| Mechanism | Biostimulation only | Fill + biostimulation | Direct fill |\n| Immediate volume | No | Yes | Yes |\n| Onset | 3-6 months (delayed) | Immediate + gradual | Immediate |\n| Duration | 2+ years | 12-18 months | 18-24 months |\n| Reversibility | Not reversible | Not reversible | Hyaluronidase |\n| FDA aesthetic indication | NLF, lipoatrophy | NLF, cheeks, hands | Cheeks, chin |\n\nGateway posture: onset and duration ranges are from published studies and FDA labels; individual outcomes vary with patient age, metabolism, treatment area, and volume treated. Product selection is a clinical judgment call based on patient anatomy, timeline expectations, and treatment goals.',
  '910b9911-dc53-47fc-a0c3-bb2eb4ee111a',
  'draft', 1
);
